<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START >: --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/mad.gif ALT=">:"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Maybe you're thinking that I was getting too good a deal, and shouldn't be surprised when someone backs out.  And I shouldn't be a baby about it.<br>
<br>
But this is what I really think:  I was willing to compensate him from the beginning.  I do think it reasonable that smiths ask for some compensation for doing what someone else cannot.  Smithing is expensive to learn; I know this well.  I even spent the day trying to figure out HOW I could compensate him indirectly (by giving him some smithing materials), since he flatly refused payment.  We reached an agreement by which we both profited; and based on that agreement, I committed my time and cash to the project.<br>
<br>
I have not been doing tradeskills for as long as some, but it seems to me that a smith or tailor or brewer or person of whatever field of expertise runs on their ability to be trusted.  The success of the combine may not be guaranteed, but the promise of fair business is based fully on trust.  You trust that the artisan will show up, has honestly represented their skill, understands the combine, and if there is a success will return the combined piece for some compensation (that you have agreed beforehand).<br>
<br>
It makes me furious that someone decides to renegotiate a promise because they think they can get a better deal.  Especially after I have committed myself in time and materials.<br>
<br>
Will he do it again?  Would you trust him enough to enter into a deal, knowing thousands of plat are committed, that he might change his mind as to what is fair during or even at the conclusion of a combine?  Even if he came back later and quoted a price, I can't trust him.  I think anyone who would is a fool.  Just makes me mad that I had to be the first to be fooled.<br>
<br>
